english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Geum, Former Grand Master of Filial Piety
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Generally, heaven's rewards are distributed such that those given horns are not given wings. Thus, among scholars who rank first in the examination and reach high office, such occurrences are rare. Yet our Minister was not of this sort. He not only topped the golden register of the examinations, but also traversed the full heights of official honor. Moreover, blessed with longevity, his entire life—from sorrow to glory—lacked nothing. How could this happen by mere chance? Surely heaven had one it could not help but favor greatly, and to such a one, though much is taken, heaven does not begrudge its gifts.

    Our Minister's given name was Yi, and his courtesy name was Jeol-ji. His earlier name was Geuk-yi, which was later changed to Yi. He descended from the lineage of Yong-sik, a merit subject of the Three Han kingdoms, and Geum-po County in Gae-yang was his ancestral home. His great-grandfather held the post of Scattered Official of the Divine Tiger Guard and was posthumously awarded Grand General. His grandfather served as Inspecting Censor of the Crown Prince's Minor Protector and was posthumously awarded Grand Commandant of the Left. His father served as Administrator of Chang-an Compound and through his son's merit was posthumously awarded Grand Commandant of the Left. His mother, of the Seo clan, was daughter of the Inspecting Commissioner of the Imperial Armory and through her son's merit was awarded the rank of Grand Lady of Riecheon.

    From youth, the Minister devoted himself to learning and excelled in composition. In the year Yi-mi he entered the National Academy, and shortly thereafter took the civil service examination. Before achieving the doctorate, he went out to administer Cheongdo County, where through earnest cultivation of integrity and virtue, through firm and upright governance without wavering, the region came to call him "the Iron Minister of Cheongdo." When his term expired, he was transferred to become Vice-Judge of the Eight Gates Treasury. The following year, he took the spring examination and was selected as the top graduate. He was thus enrolled in the Inner Service, and the throne valued and employed him greatly.

    Progressing through many offices, he rose to the rank of Minor Functionary in the Bureau of Artisans with court retinue, and was appointed Master of the Gate of Heavenly Harmony. Through his elegant and prestigious positions, he served as Supernumerary Official of the Ministry of Personnel, Direct Keeper of the Treasure Library, Left Gentleman of the Door, Gentleman Attendant on Ceremonial Occasions, Drafter of Edicts, Gentleman of the Ministry of Justice, Instructor to the Crown Prince, Direct Lecturer to the National Academy, Investigating Censor, Central Secretariat Drafter, Compiler of the National History, Gentleman of the Ministry of War, Court Attendant of the Hanlin Academy, Court Lecturer to the Eastern Palace, Right Minister of Personnel, Right Remonstrant Minister, and Excellent Counselor to the Crown Prince.

    The Minister once held concurrent posts as Dual Academy Scholar, and at this time also held three concurrent positions as Great Counselor, which brought great honor to the court. When the Minister served in the remonstrance office, there was one unfit to hold the rank of Concurrent Counselor. The Minister, together with his colleagues, firmly refused approval. The powerful resented this, and all were transferred from the Secretariat to other posts. The Minister likewise was sent out to serve as Director of the Bureau of Artisans and Master of the Gate of Heavenly Harmony—a position known as most difficult. Though it was his first attempt at this duty, his conduct was graceful and refined, surpassing even those long seasoned in the role. Such was the range of his talent. Soon after, he was appointed Right Remonstrant Minister with concurrent position as Director of the Secretariat of Secret Records. Shortly thereafter, he was appointed Right Vice-Director of the Chancellery, retaining his remonstrance position and concurrent post as Drafter of Edicts. By seniority, he became Overseer of Memorials and Director of the Ministry of Personnel.

    For many years, the Minister managed affairs of state counsel. In all his memorials and service, he greatly pleased the throne, which relied upon him heavily and consulted him on many matters of governance. In the year Imsin, an envoy from the Jin dynasty arrived wishing to enter through the main gate. Our court refused permission, and interpreters were sent to dissuade them, yet the envoys would not yield. That day heavy rain fell, and all the officials stood drenched, waiting. The throne commanded the Minister to go and reason with them. Going before them, he first asked: "When the Son of Heaven makes his progresses through the territories of the feudal lords, such has been done since ancient times. If your Great Emperor were to grace our small nation with his presence, through which gate ought he to enter?" They replied: "Through which gate but the central gate does the Son of Heaven pass?" He responded: "Then is it fitting for a subject to wish to enter through his sovereign's principal gate?" Thereupon they greatly admired his words and agreed to enter through the western gate.

    In applying expedient measures to address situations, the Minister's solutions surpassed what ordinary persons could conceive. The throne greatly praised and rewarded him. In the year Gyeyu, he was promoted to the rank of Purple-Robed Keeper of the Treasury, Vice-Director of the Chancellery, Left Attendant of the Scattered Cavalry, and Hanlin Scholar-Official. In the year Ulhai, he entered the government as Purple-Robed Grand Keeper of the Treasury, Chief Minister, Grand Commandant of the Left, Great Scholar of the Precious Library, and Editor of the National History. In the year Jeongchuk, he became Acting Grand Commandant and Gentleman of the Secretariat with concurrent position as Minister of the Right. In the year Muoin, he became Minister of the Gate and Great Scholar of the Hall of Cultivated Literature.

    Once at the Festival of the Eight Gates, when certain elements of the entertainment were not being performed according to protocol, a censor's officer rushed forward to seize and humiliate the queue-leader. The military and their commanders then made great commotion, turned about angrily, and began hurling tiles and stones at the Censorate's pavilion. Some stones even flew near the Chancellor's canopy. The Minister, greatly enraged, hastily descended to the courtyard, stood resolute, and with measured voice cried out: "Do you dare such conduct in a realm where sovereign and subject, superior and inferior, are all in their proper places? If you would truly raise rebellion, first you must kill this old minister!" Thrice he called thus, and the military's resolve gradually weakened, the uprising was prevented. Such was his fearlessness when facing peril.

    When the Minister inspected Chun province as an investigating censor, he governed officials with severe discipline and devoted all effort to eliminating harm to the people, for whom he became a great blessing. He once oversaw the examination for officials and three times supervised the civil service examinations, and those selected were all renowned figures of the age—such flourishing of talent had not been seen in recent times.

    In the year Gyeongchin, he was appointed Wall Inscribed Triple Han Great Counselor, Keeper of the Treasury, Minister of the Right, and Chief Scholar of the Hall of Cultivated Literature with concurrent directorship of the Ministry of Personnel. He then retired to his home, where together with other aged virtuous seniors he founded the Society of the Aged, gathering each day for feasts and leisurely pursuits, thereby fulfilling his joy in beneficent patronage.

    On the twenty-sixth day of the first month in the year Gyeongbin, he experienced a slight ailment. Yet that very day he had his descendants play go and watched them. As evening came, he still conversed with ease and composure. When night fell, he passed away serenely and quietly, such that even those attending him did not notice. Is this mere coincidence? He enjoyed seventy-eight years of life. When the throne heard of his passing, it was deeply grieved, and ordered the proper authorities to manage his funeral. He was buried at the foot of Phoenix Mountain and posthumously honored.

    The Minister's manner was marked by fine bearing and dignified composure. In his youth, a Song merchant named Jang Cheon-gak, skilled in physiognomy, observed him and said: "This one will surely reach the position of Chancellor." Indeed, it came to pass as he foretold. His nature was firm and resolute; when confronting others face-to-face, he concealed nothing. For this reason, many feared him, and some slandered him. Yet his heart was open and level; though people cursed him in his time, he afterward cast all aside without lingering resentment. Thus he was able to preserve himself. Truly, he was a man of open-heartedness and generous spirit.

    He married the daughter of the Grand Councillor Kim Gwang-sik and fathered five sons and three daughters. The first son, Ji, served as Supernumerary Official of the Ministry of Revenue but predeceased his father. The second, Gyu, served as Supernumerary Official of the Ministry of Works. The third, Sim-jeong, took monastic vows and became a Seon master. The fourth, Hui, served as Grand General of the Left and Right Guards but predeceased his father. The fifth, Hui, served as Master of the Gate of Heavenly Harmony but also predeceased. The sixth, Gi, served as Commander of Miscellaneous Crafts. The eldest daughter married Yin Wae-hyo, General of the Middle Rank in the Inner Service Guard. The second married Yi Deok-jae, Gentleman of the Ministry of Revenue, though she predeceased. The third married Hahm Gyeong-gyun, Master of the Gate of Heavenly Harmony.

    His sons, particularly Gyu, brought forth his record of conduct and earnestly requested an epitaph. Thus I have composed the following:

    Who counseled the imperial court,
    And gave great voice to his nation?
    Our worthy Keeper of the Realm—
    Indeed the foremost of his kind.
    Up through the halls of power he rose,
    With firm resolve and upright bearing,
    Corrupt officials trembled and bowed,
    As righteous judgment held its sway.

    The principal gate stands high and proud,
    None dare approach its sacred threshold,
    Yet foreign envoys, soiled of foot,
    Sought to trespass there unbidden.
    Our Minister came forth to reason,
    With but a single word struck true—
    Even those of bestial hearts
    Were moved to understanding.

    For the realm he formed wise counsel,
    Both clear and deep in thought,
    Returned at last to verdant fields,
    To wander free and unconfined.
    On immortal chariot he departed,
    To distant paths beyond the clouds—
    The old worthies now are gone,
    Who else can serve as our example?

    Phoenix Mountain stands eternal,
    Its gentle slopes receive the honored dead,
    Where fertile earth and sweet springs flow,
    And verdant groves grow thick and green.
    Here finds his rest the worthy soul,
    This dwelling-place so justly made—
    We inscribe these words in stone,
    That his radiance shall endure without end.
